07290nam a22012495i 9780691214665DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20202008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912146657 a10.1515/97806912146652doi  a(DE-B1597)563236  a(OCoLC)1191864271  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aBUS0690302bisacsh04a38100aDo Economists Make Markets? :bOn the Performativity of Economics /ced. by Donald MacKenzie, Fabian Muniesa, Lucia Siu. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b6 halftones. 11 line illus. 6 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations, Boxes, and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. The Social Construction of a Perfect Market: The Strawberry Auction at Fontaines-en-Sologne -- tChapter 3. Is Economics Performative? Option Theory and the Construction of Derivatives Markets -- tChapter 4. Decoding Finance: Articulation and Liquidity around a Trading Room -- tChapter 5. How to Do Things with Experimental Economics -- tChapter 6. Economic Experiments and the Construction of Markets -- tChapter 7. Markets Made Flesh: Performativity, and a Problem in Science Studies, Augmented with Consideration of the FCC Auctions -- tChapter 8. Which Way Is Up on Callon? -- tChapter 9. The Properties of Markets -- tChapter 10. Do Statistics "Perform" the Economy? -- tChapter 11. What Does It Mean to Say That Economics Is Performative? -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAround the globe, economists affect markets by saying what markets are doing, what they should do, and what they will do. Increasingly, experimental economists are even designing real-world markets. But, despite these facts, economists are still largely thought of as scientists who merely observe markets from the outside, like astronomers look at the stars. Do Economists Make Markets? boldly challenges this view. It is the first book dedicated to the controversial question of whether economics is performative--of whether, in some cases, economics actually produces the phenomena it analyzes. The book's case studies--including financial derivatives markets, telecommunications-frequency auctions, and individual transferable "as in fisheries--give substance to the notion of the performativity of economics in an accessible, nontechnical way. Some chapters defend the notion; others attack it vigorously. The book ends with an extended chapter in which Michel Callon, the idea's main formulator, reflects upon the debate and asks what it means to say economics is performative. The book's insights and strong claims about the ways economics is entangled with the markets it studies should interest--and provoke--economic sociologists, economists, and other social scientists. In addition to the editors and Callon, the contributors include Marie-France Garcia-Parpet, Francesco Guala, Emmanuel Didier, Philip Mirowski, Edward Nik-Khah, Petter Holm, Vincent-Antonin Lépinay, and Timothy Mitchell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomics. 0aMarkets. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh  aBayesian learning.  aHomo economicus.  aNobel Prizes.  aabstraction.  aarticulation.  abank run.  abrokers.  acollaterals.  aconcentration of wealth.  acooperatives.  acyborgs.  adead capital.  adispossession.  aeconomic engineering.  aembeddedness.  aexperimental economics.  aexpertise.  afinancial engineering.  aframing.  agovernments.  ahybridization.  aidentities.  ain vivo.  alaboratories.  alegality.  alive capital.  amanipulations.  a